    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Describe the bug\n\nWhen casting different types to `<bool>`, the behaviour seems inconsistent.\n\n\n### Code to reproduce the behaviour:\n\n```cython\n# [1]\ncdef int int_x = 5\ncdef int int_bool_int_x = <int> <bool> int_x\n# TypeError: Expected bool, got int\n\n# [2]\ncdef object x = 5\ncdef char c = <char> <bint> x\n# c = 1\ncdef object x = 5\ncdef char c = <char> bool(x)\n# c = 1\ncdef object x = 5\ncdef char c = <char> <bool> x\n# c = 5\n\n# [3]\ncdef object x = 555\ncdef char c = <char> <bool> x\n# OverflowError: value too large to convert to char\n```\n\n\n### Expected behaviour\n\n1) We currently convert the C `int` to PyLong, then cast to PyBool (which fails in the type check) and then convert the result to C `int`. We should instead obey the cast and convert the C `int` to PyBool, then to C `int`. If we want to optimise, the way is through `bint` instead of  `bool`.\nI would consider a successful conversion more helpful here than a (compile time) failure.\n\n2) I think the `<bool>` cast ~should actually fail at runtime because~ we are trying to cast a Python object that is not `bool` to `bool`. If users want to do this, they can use `<bint>` or `bool()` to get an explicit conversion instead of a mere Python type cast. EDIT: We don't do type checks for explicit casts, so this is not a runtime error.\nWe might also want to issue warnings when users cast between incompatible known Python types (although that doesn't apply to `object` in this example code).\n\n3) This is more or less the same as [2] and should fail with a `TypeError` on the first cast, not get through to the second.\n\n**Alternatively:**\nWe could consider `<bool>` the Python equivalent of `<bint>` and always implement it as a truthiness test.\nThis wouldn't be quite in line with other Python types casts (which enforce a type tests), but would match the current behaviour of Python typed function arguments:\n\n```cython\ndef bool_arg(x: bool):\n    return x\n\n# bool_arg(0) -> False\n# bool_arg(1) -> True\n# bool_arg(12345) -> True\n```\n\nOne issue with this is that we'd introduce several ways to do it (`bool()`, `<bint>`, `<bool>` would all do the same thing), but without a way to get an actual `bool` type cast with type check if there is need for that. Users would have to resort to `isinstance()` and implement the error themselves. Not difficult, but it might be surprising to users that this is required, compared to other Python builtin type casts.\n\nGiven \"explicit is better than implicit\",\n**my proposal is**:\n\n- ~Make `<bool>` an explicit type cast and reject non-bool Python types.~\n- Let `<bool>` work on C types but make the result always True/False or 0/1 (when aliasing to `bint`). Use the C type specific truthiness test for the conversion. (NOTE: this is really optional – it seems perfectly ok to require `bool()` or `<bint>` instead of allowing a cast to `bool`.)\n- Require `bool()` or `<bint>` for boolean type conversions and (continue to) translate them to a truthiness test internally.\n\n### OS\n\n_No response_\n\n### Python version\n\n_No response_\n\n### Cython version\n\nmaster\n\n### Additional context\n\nThis also applies to older Cython versions but should not change in a point release.",
